I have in the past  mused about the  idea of a market maker for mergers and=
 acquisitions.[1] Like, you run a public company, you want to sell it, you =
go to an investment bank for advice. =E2=80=9CWe think you could sell your =
company for $10 billion to $12 billion,=E2=80=9D the bank tells you, =E2=80=
=9Cwith a well-run auction process in which we contact a dozen or so potent=
ial strategic and financial buyers. To maximize value=C2=A0we might want to=
 separate out your crown-jewel widgets business and sell it separately to a=
 strategic acquirer, while selling the non-core sprockets and gizmos lines =
to other buyers. We could have a signed deal in three months if we work=C2=
=A0every weekend.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t have time for all that =
stuff,=E2=80=9D you reply. =E2=80=9CWhy don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0you=C2=A0just pa=
y me $10 billion right now, and you take the company, and=C2=A0then=C2=A0yo=
u go figure out how to split up the company and find buyers and maximize pr=
ice? If you get $12 billion for it then hey super you=E2=80=99re up $2=C2=
=A0billion but that=E2=80=99s not my problem, just give me my money now.=E2=
=80=9DInvestment banks mostly don=E2=80=99t do this, but I guess there=E2=
=80=99s no reason why they couldn=E2=80=99t. Take some inventory risk on so=
me companies in order to facilitate liquidity for the sellers of those comp=
anies, and in exchange get, you know, orders of magnitude bigger fees than =
they=E2=80=99d get for basic M&A advice, plus potential huge upside (or dow=
nside) if the companies=E2=80=99 value goes up (or down). Of course when I =
write it out you can see the reasons that they don=E2=80=99t. Big investmen=
t banks are public companies who want stable recurring revenue, not a bunch=
 of huge lumpy=C2=A0gains and losses from owning companies briefly. Smaller=
 investment banks don=E2=80=99t have the capital to go around buying multib=
illion-dollar companies from their clients to flip them. Still it might be=
=C2=A0a useful service if someone could provide it.I know, arguably=C2=A0pr=
ivate equity=C2=A0is in the business of providing it, but not really. PE fu=
nds operate on a different time scale. They have multi-year holding periods=
 and operating expertise; their goal is not so much to bridge buyers and se=
llers of companies by holding inventory (of companies) for a bit and collec=
ting a spread for their service, but to pick good companies whose value wil=
l go up.[2] They are not market makers but proprietary buy-and-hold investo=
rs.This, from Sujeet Indap and James Fontanella-Khan=C2=A0at the Financial =
Times, is cool:This week shareholders of Veoneer, a Swedish auto parts make=
r listed in the US, are expected to approve a $4.5bn takeover that pays the=
m a lofty 85 per cent premium to the company=E2=80=99s pre-deal trading pri=
ce.What stands out about the deal is its structure. The auction for Veoneer=
 was won in October by a start-up New York investment firm called SSW Partn=
ers. The firm had never executed a transaction, had raised no dedicated buy=
out fund and maintained only a bare-bones website. ...The structure of thei=
r pending agreement with Veoneer has drawn the attention of the mergers and=
 acquisitions industry. It reimagines how big corporations buy pieces of co=
mpanies that would otherwise need to be acquired as a whole, deploying the =
bounty of private capital sloshing around the world while keeping financial=
 disclosures to a minimum.Qualcomm found itself in a jam this summer before=
 the SSW arrangement took shape. The California company was interested in V=
eoneer=E2=80=99s autonomous vehicle software business with which it already=
 had a joint venture. But the Sweden-based company had in July agreed to se=
ll itself for $3.8bn to Magna International, a car parts supplier.Making a =
rival bid for all of Veoneer made little sense to Qualcomm as it had no int=
erest in the remaining divisions. Yet Veoneer preferred to be sold in full.=
Qualcomm would then turn to an unknown private capital firm: SSW.The result=
ing bid bested Magna=E2=80=99s. Under a novel structure, SSW will acquire =
=E2=80=9Call the outstanding capital stock of Veoneer,=E2=80=9D and then im=
mediately sell the autonomous vehicle software unit to Qualcomm, according =
to a press release describing the transaction. SSW is to then =E2=80=9Clead=
 the process of finding strong, long-term strategic partners=E2=80=9D for V=
eoneer=E2=80=99s remaining auto parts businesses, indicating its intention =
sell them.=C2=A0SSW is three big-name banker types (Eric Schwartz, formerly=
 of Goldman;=C2=A0Joshua Steiner, formerly of Quadrangle Group, who also se=
rves as a senior advisor at Bloomberg L.P., where he was previously Head of=
 Industry Verticals; and Antonio Weiss, formerly of Lazard) who will buy Ve=
oneer, hand over the autonomous-vehicle business to Qualcomm, and keep the =
rest themselves to run a sales process. Veoneer gets to sell what it wants =
(the entire company), Qualcomm gets to buy what it wants (the autonomous-ve=
hicle business), and SSW bridges the transaction with its own capital and f=
igures out what to do with the remainder. Indap and Fontanella-Khan write:T=
hose close to the deal said that SSW was approached because the traditional=
 way of divesting unwanted assets =E2=80=94 having the buyer simply sell of=
f unwanted units piecemeal =E2=80=94 was usually distracting and destroyed =
value. A typical private equity partner might not have been as flexible as =
SSW, said these people.It is not totally clear that this way of divesting u=
nwanted assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0have them owned by some investment bankers tr=
ying to=C2=A0flip them =E2=80=94=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t be distracting or destr=
oy value, but it=E2=80=99s fun to find out. From the press release announci=
ng the deal:=E2=80=9CWe are excited to partner with Qualcomm to acquire Veo=
neer,=E2=80=9D said Antonio Weiss and Josh Steiner of SSW Partners. =E2=80=
=9CWhile Qualcomm focuses on the Arriver business, we will focus on finding=
 strong, long-term strategic homes for the rest of Veoneer=E2=80=99s busine=
sses =E2=80=93 we are committed to ensuring that Veoneer=E2=80=99s employee=
s prosper, the businesses continue to innovate and grow and customers conti=
nue to have uninterrupted access to the outstanding service and quality for=
 which Veoneer is known. We have high regard for Veoneer=E2=80=99s manageme=
nt team and look forward to partnering with them to ensure a successful out=
come for all stakeholders.=E2=80=9DMaybe that=E2=80=99s cool? To be owned f=
or a few months by some bankers working on a flip? If Qualcomm bought the w=
hole thing, integrated the part it wanted, and tried to sell the parts it d=
idn=E2=80=99t, the people in those unwanted parts would feel pretty unloved=
. The Qualcomm executives would be focused on maximizing the long-term valu=
e of the stuff they=C2=A0were keeping, and would not lavish a lot of attent=
ion on the stuff they were selling. Whereas SSW will earn its money by maki=
ng the leftover stuff as pretty as possible until it can sell. I don=E2=80=
=99t think they have a ton of incentives to cut corners or neglect the busi=
ness as they try to sell it? If your house is on the market you keep it cle=
an and spring for fresh flowers.Now, it=E2=80=99s not clear that SSW=C2=A0e=
xactly has =E2=80=9Cits own capital,=E2=80=9D and it is not exactly an inve=
stment bank.=C2=A0(It=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ca Delaware limited partnership bas=
ed in New York that invests in high-quality businesses and collaborates wit=
h partners to create enduring value for all stakeholders,=E2=80=9D says Veo=
neer=E2=80=99s merger proxy. The press release says: =E2=80=9CSSW Partners=
=E2=80=99 investment in Veoneer will represent its first capital commitment=
 as a partnership since its founding at the beginning of the year.=E2=80=9D=
) Indap and Fontanella-Khan write:SSW has not disclosed who is providing it=
s portion of the acquisition financing. It is not relying on debt financing=
, according to a person close to the firm. =E2=80=A6 But its founders have =
historical ties to large global investors.=C2=A0And Qualcomm is effectively=
 backstopping SSW=E2=80=99s financing: Qualcomm is on the hook to buy all o=
f Veoneer if SSW doesn=E2=80=99t show up with financing.There is a lot of a=
d hoc capital out there these days. The traditional way to take a company p=
ublic is that you go to an investment bank, the investment bank sells your =
shares to the public, the price you get depends on what the public market w=
ill pay, and the bank gets a cash fee when it finishes. The 2021 way to tak=
e a company public is with a SPAC, a special purpose acquisition company: A=
 sponsor raises an ad hoc investing pool and then takes a company public at=
 a negotiated-in-advance=C2=A0price using the money in the investing pool, =
and is rewarded with a chunk of the company and potentially huge upside.[3]=
 Instead of going to a bank acting as agent, you go to a SPAC sponsor actin=
g as principal, backed by a pool of capital.The traditional way to sell a c=
ompany is that you go to an investment bank, the investment bank finds a bu=
yer, the price you get depends on what the buyer will pay, and the bank get=
s a cash fee when it finishes. The Veoneer way to sell the non-autonomous b=
usiness is that some sponsors raise an investing pool and then buy the busi=
ness at a negotiated price using the money from their investors, and are re=
warded with a chunk of the company and potentially huge upside. Instead of =
going to a bank acting as agent, you go to a these guys=C2=A0acting as prin=
cipal, backed by a pool of capital.
