Insider trading, I like to say, is not about fairness, it=E2=80=99s about t=
heft. It=E2=80=99s not illegal to trade on information that nobody else kno=
ws; it=E2=80=99s illegal to trade on information that you got wrongly, that=
 you had some duty not to use for your advantage or that someone had some d=
uty not to disclose to you. (This is not legal advice, of course, and is in=
 any case mostly about=C2=A0U.S.=C2=A0law; other countries often have more =
information-parity-oriented rules.)One classic case of this is that it is n=
ot generally illegal to trade on your own intentions. Most simply, if you k=
now that you want to buy stock, and nobody else does, you can still buy sto=
ck. This is true even if your buying is material to other people. If Warren=
 Buffett says =E2=80=9Chey I bought 5% of XYZ,=E2=80=9D the stock will go u=
p. But he can still buy it before announcing that. It=E2=80=99s his busines=
s. Similarly if the chief executive officer of a company says =E2=80=9Chey =
I sold all my shares,=E2=80=9D the stock will go down. But she can still se=
ll before announcing it.=C2=A0There are some tricky issues here. If you wor=
k for Warren Buffett=E2=80=99s Berkshire Hathaway Inc., and you are in the =
business of bringing him companies to buy, and you spot a great company, an=
d you write up a compelling report saying =E2=80=9CI think we should buy XY=
Z,=E2=80=9D and you put it on his desk, and then you go buy some stock in X=
YZ =E2=80=94=C2=A0there you are arguably using information that does=C2=A0n=
ot=C2=A0belong to you, that belongs to Berkshire Hathaway.[4] (The informat=
ion is not the good stuff about the company that you put in the report, whi=
ch is presumably public, but rather=C2=A0the fact that Warren Buffett might=
 buy the company, because you told him to, as part of your job.) You don=E2=
=80=99t exactly own your research, if you work at Berkshire Hathaway; Berks=
hire does.Another question is: If you do own your own plans, and your own r=
esearch, can you=C2=A0sell=C2=A0it? Can you give it away? Can you barter it=
 for something useful for you?=C2=A0If you plan to launch a hostile takeove=
r of=C2=A0a company, or an activist proxy fight,=C2=A0can you call up your =
hedge-fund buddies and say =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99m gonna go to work on Com=
pany X, I need my friends to be shareholders so they=E2=80=99ll vote for my=
 deal, why don=E2=80=99t you buy some stock now and then owe me a favor=E2=
=80=9D? Your buddies get to trade on nonpublic information (that you=E2=80=
=99re going to announce a proxy fight or=C2=A0merger proposal), and will ma=
ke money, but you own that information (it=E2=80=99s your own plans) and yo=
u=E2=80=99re giving it to them to advance your own business interests. Okay=
? Or what?[5]Or a classic is: You are in the business of finding bad compan=
ies, betting that their stocks will go down, and then putting out research =
explaining why they are bad. If your reports are good, the stocks will go d=
own and you will make money. But this is a risky and capital-intensive busi=
ness, and you might want to=C2=A0also sell=C2=A0your research to hedge fund=
s in advance. The hedge funds will also short the stock and hope to make mo=
ney when your report comes out, and they will pay you for your effort so th=
at you are not reliant on your own short-sale trades to make all your money=
.I feel like when I describe it like that:=09It seems fine to me?=09It prob=
ably doesn=E2=80=99t seem fine to normal people?Like, =E2=80=9Cevil short-s=
eller researchers are writing mean reports about public companies, and then=
 selling early access to those reports to secretive hedge funds who will be=
t against those companies, and then publishing those reports trying to mani=
pulate the companies=E2=80=99 stock prices down so the evil hedge funds wil=
l make money,=E2=80=9D that sort of thing. Again seems fine to me! (If the =
reports are true!) But not going to make you popular with (1) companies, (2=
) shareholders or (3) I am going to guess prosecutors? Anyway  here=E2=80=
=99s a story=C2=A0from Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Katia Porzecanski, Tom Scho=
enberg and Matt Robinson:The U.S. Justice Department has launched an expans=
ive criminal investigation into short selling by hedge funds and research f=
irms, scrutinizing their symbiotic relationships and hunting for signs that=
 they improperly coordinated trades or broke other laws to profit, accordin=
g to people familiar with the matter.The probe, run by the department=E2=80=
=99s fraud section with federal prosecutors in Los Angeles, is digging into=
 how hedge funds tap into research and set up their bets, especially in the=
 run-up to publication of reports that move stocks.Also here=E2=80=99s an a=
mazing follow-up from=C2=A0Claire Ballentine and Misyrlena Egkolfopoulou ab=
out  how happy this makes retail meme-stock traders. It is full of wild quo=
tes:=E2=80=9CA lot of stocks have been held down, or a lot of companies tha=
