At a big universal bank=C2=A0there are lots of different groups that are in=
 the basic business of helping clients invest and lending those clients mon=
ey, and those groups have some overlap with each other, and there will be a=
 certain amount of competition and turf battles between them. Ideally all t=
he groups at any one bank will be working toward a common goal of maximizin=
g value for the bank (and the client), and they=E2=80=99ll share resources =
and credit and not waste their time fighting each other. But in practice su=
re sometimes it will get nasty. But since you all work at the same bank, th=
ere is some final arbiter of your infighting. You go to your boss, and the =
other team goes to their boss, and your bosses go to their bosses, and thei=
r bosses go their joint boss, and the joint boss =E2=80=94=C2=A0the person =
who sits on top of the pyramid containing=C2=A0both of your teams =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0says =E2=80=9CI think private wealth should take the lead on this one=
,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Clet investment banking handle it but give half of th=
e commission credits to private banking,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cman, leave me=
 alone, you=C2=A0can work this out.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0So there are limits to ho=
w heated the rivalry can get. For instance it is not like one group at a ba=
nk would ever=C2=A0sue=C2=A0another group at the same bank? In federal cour=
t? Asking for an injunction to make the other group back off the first grou=
p=E2=80=99s clients? Well!This action arises from the ongoing efforts by J.=
P. Morgan Private Bank (the =E2=80=9CPrivate Bank=E2=80=9D) to poach Plaint=
iff Gwen Campbell=E2=80=99s relationships with her financial advisory clien=
ts following her move from Merrill Lynch to J.P. Morgan Advisors (=E2=80=9C=
J.P. Morgan=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CJPMA=E2=80=9D) in October 2020.=C2=A0After=
 J.P. Morgan aggressively recruited Campbell and persuaded her to move her =
clients with explicit contractual promises they would not be poached by oth=
er groups at the bank, the Private Bank began ruthlessly soliciting her cli=
ents, disparaging her, and preventing clients from sending assets to Campbe=
ll (and redirecting them to the Private Bank) without her consent. In recen=
t weeks, the Private Bank has significantly escalated its attacks on Campbe=
ll=E2=80=99s client relationships and thwarted her ability to execute clien=
t transactions while, after months of promising to make things right, Campb=
ell=E2=80=99s superiors at J.P. Morgan have conceded that they are powerles=
s to help. As a result of the misrepresentations and breaches by J.P. Morga=
n, Campbell is suffering irreparable harm to her business, her reputation, =
and the client goodwill that has taken her decades to build.That is from th=
e federal complaint that JPMorgan Advisors filed against JPMorgan Private B=
ank. Oh no fine it is from the federal complaint that Gwen Campbell, a mana=
ging director who runs=C2=A0a high-profile JPMorgan Advisors team (she advi=
ses Alex Rodriguez), filed against JPMorgan. The=C2=A0Financial Times expla=
ins:She has filed for a temporary restraining order against JPMorgan to res=
trict her co-workers=E2=80=99 ability to engage with her clients, as she se=
eks damages through arbitration for what she alleges is a breach of contrac=
t.In the blistering 48-page legal filing, Campbell describes the turf war b=
etween rival businesses at JPMorgan as a =E2=80=9Cshark tank=E2=80=9D, clai=
ming her co-workers have disparaged and undermined her.The bank has said Ca=
mpbell=E2=80=99s claims =E2=80=9Chave no merit and we look forward to prese=
nting the facts to the court=E2=80=9D. =E2=80=A6JPMorgan Advisors=E2=80=99 =
model is to employ financial advisers who get paid mostly on commission. Th=
e bank=E2=80=99s relationship with wealthy clients is funnelled primarily t=
hrough these advisers. The private bank also caters to rich clients but the=
y tend to have dealings with the bank as a whole.There is co-operation on t=
hings that one unit offers but the other does not. However, they also at ti=
mes compete for the same business, including lending and providing investme=
nt advice, a dynamic which can create tension.=E2=80=9CYou don=E2=80=99t fe=
el like you=E2=80=99re working at the same company. You feel like you=E2=80=
=99re working at different firms,=E2=80=9D said one former JPMorgan private=
 banker.The complaint puts forward a theory that the Private Bank has an ad=
vantage=C2=A0internally because private bankers eat less of what they kill =
than JPMorgan Advisors advisers do:Campbell was particularly wary of potent=
ial channel conflicts involving the Private Bank. The Private Bank offers m=
any services that overlap with services offered by JPMA advisors, including=
 lending and investment advisory services for high-net-worth clients. And b=
ecause of the different compensation structures for financial advisors and =
private bankers at J.P. Morgan, there are organizational incentives to shif=
t client assets from under the management of JPMA advisors to the Private B=
ank. Financial advisors, who spend years cultivating relationships and buil=
ding trust and goodwill with their clients, receive commissions or shares o=
f the revenues based on the financial products that they sell or transactio=
ns they arrange for their clients. Private bankers, however, are not expect=
ed to generate their own business from scratch and therefore are paid less,=
 receiving salaries plus bonuses that can be impacted by bringing business =
into the Private Bank. In addition, as J.P. Morgan=E2=80=99s San Francisco =
Regional Director and Campbell=E2=80=99s direct manager Steve McCashin told=
 Campbell after she arrived at J.P. Morgan, individual private bankers are =
often fueled by the prestige and power within the firm of having =E2=80=9Co=
wnership=E2=80=9D over relationships with high-profile individuals. Thus, C=
ampbell sought explicit assurances from senior management at J.P. Morgan th=
at the other divisions within the firm, particularly the Private Bank, woul=
d not compete for the client relationships she had invested so much time an=
d effort in building.I have to say I love this and wish there was more of i=
t? Bankers regularly sue their employers and colleagues when they have been=
 pushed out, etc., but I cannot think of another case where a banker stayed=
 at her bank and sued a competing internal group for poaching her clients. =
But now Campbell has shown that it is possible! If you run a group at a ban=
k, and you=E2=80=99re mad at another group for talking to your clients, now=
 you can sue them. I bet you want to!Campbell=C2=A0is also suing JPMorgan f=
or doing a bad job of setting up her work-from-home technology?Beyond the s=
ecret solicitations, J.P. Morgan has left Campbell without reliable access =
to the firm=E2=80=99s technological systems for months. Under her contract,=
 the Americans with Disabilities Act (=E2=80=9CADA=E2=80=9D), and Californi=
a=E2=80=99s Fair Employment and Housing Act (=E2=80=9CFEHA=E2=80=9D), Campb=
ell secured an accommodation to work from home throughout the COVID-19 pand=
emic because she and her son are both severely immunocompromised, requiring=
 monthly blood transfusions. For months, she has been promised access and f=
or months, JPMA has failed to deliver. No amount of begging JPMA=E2=80=99s =
IT staff or senior management for a solution has proved effective.I=E2=80=
=99ve had jobs like that! It did not occur to me to sue.
