=E2=80=99re up $2=C2=A0billion but that=E2=80=99s not my problem, just give=
 me my money now.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investment banks=
 mostly don=E2=80=99t do this, but I guess there=E2=80=99s no reason why th=
ey couldn=E2=80=99t. Take some inventory risk on some companies in order to=
 facilitate liquidity for the sellers of those companies, and in exchange g=
et, you know, orders of magnitude bigger fees than they=E2=80=99d get for b=
asic M&amp;A advice, plus potential huge upside (or downside) if the compan=
ies=E2=80=99 value goes up (or down). Of course when I write it out you can=
 see the reasons that they don=E2=80=99t. Big investment banks are public c=
ompanies who want stable recurring revenue, not a bunch of huge lumpy=C2=A0=
gains and losses from owning companies briefly. Smaller investment banks do=
n=E2=80=99t have the capital to go around buying multibillion-dollar compan=
ies from their clients to flip them. Still it might be=C2=A0a useful servic=
e if someone could provide it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I know, argu=
ably=C2=A0<em>private equity=C2=A0</em>is in the business of providing it, =
but not really. PE funds operate on a different time scale. They have multi=
-year holding periods and operating expertise; their goal is not so much to=
 bridge buyers and sellers of companies by holding inventory (of companies)=
 for a bit and collecting a spread for their service, but to pick good comp=
anies whose value will go up.[2] They are not market makers but proprietary=
 buy-and-hold investors.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26040967.308178/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMjU0ZDhjZTMtZGU3NC00M2Y1LThjYjktM2JiYWEyM2Q4Yzg0/6150=
3b55d817ff15ef6da354B51ec1108" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
